The clinical landscape of advanced melanoma drastically changed after the 
introduction of both targeted therapies and immunotherapy. This rapid 
development in systemic therapies led to a change in the management of patients 
with brain metastases, with the subsequent need to re-assess the role of local 
therapies, in particular stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS). Areas covered: In this 
non-systematic review, we report on the current knowledge on the use of SRS in 
combination with immunotherapy and BRAF/MEK inhibitors for patients with 
melanoma brain metastases, as well as ongoing trials in this field. Expert 
commentary: It is now more common to observe patients with melanoma brain 
metastases with better performance status and prolonged life expectancy. A 
combination of targeted therapy and immunotherapy, in different sequences, has 
been shown to be feasible and well tolerable, on the basis of retrospective 
reports. Additional data from ongoing prospective trials are however needed to 
confirm or not these findings and better explore the efficacy of the 
combination.

